2026-04-16 12:23:06 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['sensor-operated relay contacts in control (ambient sensor) module'] hypothesis_explanation='The control module receives a solid 11.99 V from the power supply, but only about 0.36 V appears at the relay output and at the control-module output terminals, both when the lamp is on and during the 20‑s interruptions. This means the relay is never actually delivering the full supply voltage to the load side. The output voltage level is too high to be a simple open circuit with no load, and too low for a correctly closed contact, indicating a high-resistance or intermittently conducting relay contact (or its solder joints/PCB trace) dropping most of the 12 V under the lamp load.\n\nThe absence of any response to the timing potentiometer adjustments and the fixed, low output voltage despite the stable 12 V input rule out the power supply, external wiring, and the load module as root causes. The defect is localized to the switching element inside the control module—specifically the sensor-operated relay contacts or their immediate PCB connection—causing unreliable conduction and apparent periodic flicker as the contact resistance or micro‑movement changes with time. Replacing/repairing this relay/contact assembly should restore a constant ~12 V at the control output and stop the periodic lamp outages.'
