Inthis case, also observe the following rule:
Critical rule — polarity inversions:
If a (+)-labeled cable or port is connected to a (−)-labeled cable or port (or vice versa), you MUST
explicitly state this as a POLARITY INVERSION and name the affected cables. Do not describe such a
connection as "correct" or "nominal". Example: "POLARITY INVERSION DETECTED: PSU Output Cable (+)
is connected to Control Input Cable (−), and PSU Output Cable (−) is connected to Control Input Cable (+). 
Of course, the presence of a small negative current in one cable, by itself, does not amount to polarity inversion. "


ACTION:
With the control module open and using the control-module negative as reference, measure the DC voltage at the relay coil terminals and at the output of the comparator / driver transistor that controls the relay, while the system operates through at least one 20‑second flicker cycle. Verify (a) whether the relay coil ever sees about the full supply voltage (~12 V) or only a very low value similar to the 0.36 V seen on the relay output, and (b) whether the coil voltage or driver output varies in sync with the 20‑second on/off of the lamp. This will reveal whether the low relay‑output voltage is due to the relay never being properly energized (fault in the coil or its driver/sensor circuit) versus an intermittent series element elsewhere.
